snippet.textDisplay:
Tennessee was able to prevent Jackson from doing as much damage w/ his arm as his cleats (he ran 20 times for 143 yards; that's hardly "stopping" anyone.) Jackson was picked-off twice vs. one throwing TD.

The Red Zone proved an issue for Baltimore. Henry was the unstoppable force for the Titans; incredible on the ground and threw a TD pass himself (for 3 yards but so what?) Tannehill tossed two TD's and basically turned things over to Henry. The 45th player chosen in his draft (but just the 2nd RB chosen after that Cowboy fellow) has been one heck of a player.

In fact he was the 4th Titan taken in his draft; one lasted two years and another wasn't offered an extension after this year. Talk about exceeding expectations. Henry might be today's Eric Dickerson; he keeps it up he's in that conversation.

snippet.textDisplay: I don't agree that they punch first and don't come from behind.  They have shown that they are consistent and can play good football.  There were a couple of regular season games where they came from behind and played hard through the end of the year.  I think you have a Ravens team that was recovering from the flu they had last week, the Titan's defense clearly did a good job os stopping the quarterback run game and forcing more throwing that caused more turnovers.  The 4 attempts to convert the 4th down were stopped and that was the biggest issue.  Next year is in question for sure if other teams study how TT were able to block those holes that Lamar used to get through and "transform" football.  I think many teams wee not used to the quarterback running as much as Lamar does but since TT had more time to study his style specifically during the break, they were clearly ready for it.  That, to me, puts next year in question and whether that unique style will continue to upset more traditional defenses.  It is clear to me that, if not for the crazy turnovers, this game could have been much closer and the Ravens could be on their way to the Superbowl.  Ravens fans are about as unhappy as Patriots fans are right now I suppose.  Not a great day but it has been an exciting 10 weeks.  On the bright side, Lamar did good things for Baltimore, giving a much needed boost to sports fans who are still dealing with a losing Orioles team and other major issues.  See you next year!
